	abstract = {We analyze orbital solutions for 48 massive multiple-star systems in the Cygnus OB2 association, 23 of which are newly presented here, to find that the observed distribution of orbital periods is approximately uniform in log P for P {\textless} 45 days, but it is not scale-free. Inflections in the cumulative distribution near 6 days, 14 days, and 45 days suggest key physical scales of sime0.2, sime0.4, and sime1 A.U. where yet-to-be-identified phenomena create distinct features. No single power law provides a statistically compelling prescription, but if features are ignored, a power law with exponent $\beta$ {\textasciitilde}= -0.22 provides a crude approximation over P = 1.4-2000 days, as does a piece-wise linear function with a break near 45 days. The cumulative period distribution flattens at P {\textgreater} 45 days, even after correction for completeness, indicating either a lower binary fraction or a shift toward low-mass companions. A high degree of similarity (91\% likelihood) between the Cyg OB2 period distribution and that of other surveys suggests that the binary properties at P {\textless}{\textasciitilde} 25 days are determined by local physics of disk/clump fragmentation and are relatively insensitive to environmental and evolutionary factors. Fully 30\% of the unbiased parent sample is a binary with period P {\textless} 45 days. Completeness corrections imply a binary fraction near 55\% for P {\textless} 5000 days. The observed distribution of mass ratios 0.2 {\textless} q {\textless} 1 is consistent with uniform, while the observed distribution of eccentricities 0.1 {\textless} e {\textless} 0.6 is consistent with uniform plus an excess of e {\textasciitilde}= 0 systems. We identify six stars, all supergiants, that exhibit aperiodic velocity variations of {\textasciitilde}30 km s-1 attributed to atmospheric fluctuations.},
